def: A house or mansion. [Sp. Amer. & Phil. Islands]

Capable of being dissolved, or separated into component parts;capable of being liquefied; soluble.-- Dis*solv"a*ble*ness, n.Though everything which is compacted be in its own naturedissolvable. Cudworth.Such things as are not dissolvable by the moisture of the tongue. SirI. Newton.

The art or practice of using the manual alphabet or ofcommunicating thoughts by sings made by the hands and fingers; asubstitute for spoken or written language in intercourse with thedeaf and dumb. See Dactylalogy.
A viverrine animal of Madagascar (Cryptoprocta ferox). Itresembles a cat in size and form, and has retractile claws.

A soldier especially expert and well drilled, who takes hisplace in front of a military company, as a guide for the others intheir exercises; a file leader. He originally stood in front of theright wing. [Written also flugelman.]
The act of vitiating, or the state of being vitiated;depravation; corruption; invalidation; as, the vitiation of theblood; the vitiation of a contract.The vitiation that breeds evil acts. G. Eliot.
A piece of plate armor for the head of a war horse; a tester.
A coarse stuff, usually of cotton, originally made in India.Also, an imitation of this fabric made for export.
A word of opposite meaning; a counterterm; -- used as acorrelative of synonym. [R.] C. J. Smith.
